      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Lewis Carroll (Charles Lutwidge Dodgson) (1832-1898) was an English author,  mathematician, and Anglican deacon best known for his children's books <emph render="italic">Alice's Adventures in Wonderland</emph> and <emph render="italic"> Through the Looking-Glass</emph>.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The<emph render="bold"> Lewis Carroll Letters</emph> contains 7 letters written by Carroll. The letters span 1882 to 1892 and are addressed to a variety of corespondents. They consist of 1 letter dated 1890 to an unknown minister, 2 letters dated 1890 to an unknown archdeacon, 2 letters and 1 card dated 1882 and 1892 to Carroll's friend Edith Blakemore, and 1 letter with an unknown date sent to another friend Enid Stevens (later Enid Shawyer). All were sent from his residence at Christ Church, Oxford.</p><p>The  letters and cards addressed to Blakemore are also accompanied by two gift pincushions. </p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>The Blakemore letters are mounted together in a scrapbook and the other items are in chronological order.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
      <relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
         <head>Related Material</head>
         <p>&scrc_name; holds many different editions of <emph render="italic">Alice's Adventures in Wonderland</emph> as part of its children's book and illustration collections.</p>
      </relatedmaterial>
      
